    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "i get that it's a debate, but like, if we're talking about legal theory, isn't it more \"grounded\" to stick to what was actually written at the time? the living constitution idea feels a bit like people just making up rules as they go to fit their own politics. don't you think originalism is a more objective way to look at it?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Originalism offers a powerful appeal to objectivity by anchoring legal interpretation to the historical understanding of the document. The idea is that if the text's meaning is fixed at the time of ratification, the law achieves a degree of stability independent of current political winds. However, critics argue that historical context is always incomplete, making any \"original\" understanding inherently subjective and prone to bias. Therefore, while originalism seeks objectivity, it demands a very rigid and precise definition of what the Founders actually meant.",
      "source": "target",
